commentBody:
@Mike 

I'd rather use my logarithmic rule instead.

But I'll let it slide.

@Mike

Back in the day (1980s) it was very common for proprietors of small shops in Japan to add up purchases in an abacus.

Their kids may not have been so adept, and thus the introduction of the abacus with a built-in calculator. Not sure if those are still sold!

@Barry Ancona 

Hah, I even remembered that Sandra Lee was Governor Cuomo's girlfriend for a while.

And it's been a long, long time since I spent any time in the area.

@Disco Volante I’ve got two classmates who became newsworthy.

One got national attention when he was running a used car lot and ran a “buy a car, get a free gun” promo.

The other, who bullied me in elementary school, is now in prison for murdering his mother for money to buy drugs,

@Nancy. J 

You "cottoned" to the theme.  LOL.  Good one.  (I guess you were on the right track). 

The train that inspired Libba Cotten's song is about a mile from my house.  That train only comes about once a week now, and has to leave the same way it entered the town of Carrboro as it dead ends at the UNC plant.

@Lewis 

Love it! That's the countdown I've been waiting for!





Emus -- cue up Bowie's "Space Oddity"!

@Heg 

If you’re talking about the puzzle title, it’s in the app. Click on the i icon and you will find it. 

Crew is a synonym for rowing. So it’s not as redundant as you think.

@Ann Daniels 
Spelling them out should have worked just fine.
(I always print and solve, so I can't imagine how tiny stuff must be on your phone...)

@Bluevoter 

I had one. Broke it on my only trip to NYC. It was my favorite phone of the approximately 10 I've owned. (One every 2.5 years sounds right.) 

Currently on my second Pixel. Decent phones. Not as good as the LG K20 V I had in 2017. I loved the double tap!

@Stephanie
COWPOX isn't much better!  Yuck!!






emu food

@Peri 

I thought the clue was refering to Roman numerals.

Your assumption that no one at the NYT  crossword department knows algebra is likely incorrect.

@Barry Ancona

Enter 10 but read it as t-e-n and it still makes sense. Extra brain step but a puzzle with a gimmick can work several ways, especially since it was clear from the title that numbers were involved somehow. I think the numerals actually made it a little more fun. 

Again, I really enjoyed the puzzle. I just don’t like having to check hints/spoilers to figure out how I’m supposed to enter it on the app.

@Barry Ancona 
Doll, I live 10 minutes from Paramus. that was the easy one...
Finally figured out what was going on. Thanks, though..

@Anna how wonderful to hear such a progress report! 

I've been doing the NYT for at least 53 years, starting in high school, and still delight in the "aha!" moment I get when working an imaginatively constructed puzzle like today's. 

Keep it up and you'll be solving without google and autocheck in no time!

@RDB 

If you have the new app, the archives are on the main page under the big crossword icon.

I had the new app for a bit, then it reverted back for some reason. Not complaining - the new app didn't seem to offer much new, and added clicks for some things.

@Alan Parker 

To get the intended phrases, you need to read downward at the number word and then resume the Across clue from the next Across square.  So it’s ALUM(NINE)WSLETTER. 

Do enough puzzles, and you’ll probably understand what to look for better, and like them more.
